  <discussion>endemic</discussion>
  <discussion>illustrated</discussion>
  <discussion>Plants of Berberis nervosa are usually very low (commonly 0.1-0.3 m), but occasional plants may be considerably taller (to 2 m). One such population from north of Westport, California, has been separated as B. nervosa var. mendocinensis. Similar populations occur sporadically throughout the range of B. nervosa, so the form should not be recognized taxonomically.</discussion>
  <discussion>Berberis nervosa is resistant to infection by Puccinia graminis.</discussion>
  <discussion>The Skagit tribe used Berberis nervosa medicinally in a root preparation to treat venereal disease (D. E. Moermann 1986).</discussion>
